ty Cork, Irland","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Irland","Castletown, Kildrought, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kilkenny, Irland","Bunratty Castle, Connaught, Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Bunratty Castle, County Clare, Irland"},"nl":{"1429–":"1429–Overleden","1429–Male":"1429–Overleden","1456–1517":"1456–1517","1455–1513":"1455–1513","1395–1444":"1395–1444","1399–1463":"1399–1463","1547":"1547","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1429":"1429","1517":"1517","abt 1420":"circa 1420","Barry Roe, Cork, Ireland":"Barryroe, County Cork, Ierland","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Ierland","Castletown, Kildrought, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kilkenny, Ierland","Bunratty Castle, Connaught, Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Bunratty Castle, County Clare, Ierland"},"en":{"1429–":"1429–Deceased","1429–Male":"1429–Deceased","1456–1517":"1456–1517","1455–1513":"1455–1513","1395–1444":"1395–1444","1399–1463":"1399–1463","1547":"1547","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1429":"1429","1517":"1517","abt 1420":"about 1420","Barry Roe, Cork, Ireland":"Barryroe, County Cork, Ireland","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland","Castletown, Kildrought, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kilkenny, Ireland","Bunratty Castle, Connaught, Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Bunratty Castle, County Clare, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."],"variants":[{"name":"Barr","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow) and northern Irish (Ulster): habitational name from any of various places in southwestern Scotland, in particular Ayrshire and Renfrewshire, named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’ or a Brittonic cognate of this.","English and Welsh: habitational name from Great Barr in Staffordshire. This is from Brittonic <i>barro-</i> ‘top, summit’, referring to Barr Beacon; there is evidence that this was known as <i>la Bare</i> in the 13th century.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Barre-en-Ouche in Eure, France, or perhaps from Barre-de-Semilly in Manche, France."]},{"name":"Barrie","meanings":["Scottish (Angus): habitational name from Barry in Angus or from another place so named, generally named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’, or from a British cognate of this word. This name is also the Scottish form of   Barry  .","French (<b>Barrié</b>): variant of   Barrier  .","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]},{"name":"Berry","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."]},{"name":"Dubarry","meanings":["French: variant of the topographic or habitational name   Barry  , with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’."]},{"name":"Baril","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Alain, Armand, Ghislaine, Jacques, Jean-Marc, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Monique, Phillippe.","French: from Old French <i>baril</i> ‘barrel’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a cooper, or a nickname for a rotund man. Compare   Barry   7 and   Berry   7.","History: Jean Baril from the Saintonge region of France was in QC by 1673, when he married Marie Guillet, the first of his three wives. He died in 1724 in Batiscan, QC. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Barrie</i>, <i>Bar(r)y</i>, and <i>Berry</i>."]},{"name":"Bary","meanings":["Walloon and northern French: variant of   Barry   8.","French (southern): rare variant of   Barry   6.","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitzjohn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   John  , ‘son of  <i>John</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]},{"name":"Fidgeon","meanings":["1  English: (i) variant of   Vivian  .  Compare  Videan  . (ii) variant of   Fitzjohn  .","2  Irish: reduced variant of  <b>Mag Guagáin</b>,  see  McGuigan  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355924,"age":118,"year":"1547","julianDay":2286090,"description":"Henry VIII dies, succeeded by the boy king Edward VI. England and Ireland were ruled by the senior nobility of England.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When James Fitzjohn Barry was born in 1429, in Barryroe, County Cork, Ireland, his father, Lawrence The Barry Roe Barry, was 35 and his mother, Princess Orlagg O'Brien Thomond, was 31. He married Lady Joan FitzGerald Lady of Kilkenny 2nd Baroness of Barry Roe in 1473, in Castletown, County Kilkenny, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1429–":"1429–Surnud","1429–Male":"1429–Surnud","1456–1517":"1456–1517","1455–1513":"1455–1513","1395–1444":"1395–1444","1399–1463":"1399–1463","1547":"1547","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1429":"1429","1517":"1517","abt 1420":"umbes 1420","Barry Roe, Cork, Ireland":"Barryroe, County Cork, Iirimaa","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Castletown, Kildrought, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kilkenny, Iirimaa","Bunratty Castle, Connaught, Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Bunratty Castle, County Clare, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1429–":"1429–Kuollut","1429–Male":"1429–Kuollut","1456–1517":"1456–1517","1455–1513":"1455–1513","1395–1444":"1395–1444","1399–1463":"1399–1463","1547":"1547","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1429":"1429","1517":"1517","abt 1420":"noin 1420","Barry Roe, Cork, Ireland":"Barryroe, County Cork, Irlanti","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Irlanti","Castletown, Kildrought, Kilkenny, Leinster, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kilkenny, Irlanti","Bunratty Castle, Connaught, Kingdom of Thomond, Ireland":"Bunratty Castle, County Clare, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1429–":"1429–Décédé","1429–Male":"1429–Décédé","1456–1517":"1456–1517","1455–1513":"1455–1513","1395–1444":"1395–1444","1399–1463":"1399–1463","1547":"1547","1513":"1513","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1473":"1473","1395":"1395","1429":"1429","1517":"1517","abt 1420":"environ 1420","Barry Roe, Cork, Ireland":"Barryroe, County Cork, Irlande","Castletown, County Kildare, Ireland":"Castletown, County Kildare, Ir